(Loan Data from Prosper Exploration )¶

by (Nada Alkhalaf)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

def plot_correlation_map( df ):
    corr = df.corr()
    _ , ax = plt.subplots( figsize =( 6 , 12 ) )
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette( 240 , 10 , as_cmap = True )
    plt.title('Correlation Plot') 
    _ = sns.heatmap(corr,cmap = cmap,square=True, cbar_kws={ 'shrink' : .41 }, ax=ax, annot = True, annot_kws = { 'fontsize' : 12 })

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.
# can use a larger sample since there are fewer plots and they're simpler in nature.
# {'LoanStatus': {'Chargedoff': 1, 'Completed': 2, 'Current': 3, 'Defaulted': 4, 
# 'FinalPaymentInProgress': 5, 'Past Due (1-15 days)': 6, 'Past Due (16-30 days)': 7, 
# 'Past Due (31-60 days)': 8, 'Past Due (61-90 days)': 9, 'Past Due (91-120 days)': 10, 'Past Due (>120 days)': 11}}
def box_plot(data):
    categoric_vars = data
    samples = np.random.choice(df_temp.shape[0], 2000, replace = False)
    Loan_samp = df_temp.loc[samples,:]

    def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
        """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
        default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
        
        sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

    plt.figure(figsize = [15, 15])
    sns.set_context("paper", rc={"font.size":12,"axes.titlesize":12,"axes.labelsize":12})
    g = sns.PairGrid(data = Loan_samp, y_vars = ['LoanStatus'], x_vars = categoric_vars,
                    height = 5, aspect = 1.5)
    g.map(boxgrid)
    plt.show();

def countplot():
    plt.figure(figsize = [40, 40])
    sns.set_context("paper", rc={"font.size":40,"axes.titlesize":40,"axes.labelsize":40})
    # subplot 1: Term vs LoanStatus
    plt.subplot(3, 1, 1)
    sns.countplot(data = df_clean, x = 'Term', hue = 'LoanStatus', palette = 'Blues')
    plt.legend(prop={'size': 20})
    # subplot 2: IncomeVerifiable vs LoanStatus
    ax = plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)
    sns.countplot(data = df_clean, x = 'IncomeVerifiable', hue = 'LoanStatus', palette = 'Blues')
    ax.legend(ncol = 2,prop={'size': 20}) # re-arrange legend to reduce overlapping

    # subplot 3: EmploymentStatus vs LoanStatus
    ax = plt.subplot(3, 1, 3)
    sns.countplot(data = df_clean, x = 'EmploymentStatus', hue = 'LoanStatus', palette = 'Blues')
    ax.legend(loc = 1, ncol = 2,prop={'size': 20}) # re-arrange legend to remove overlapping

    plt.show()

  • (IsBorrowerHomeowner and loanstatuse)and(IncomeVerifiableand loanstatuse): the two plots are very similar, i think this feature doesn’t really affect the loan statues.

  • Term vs LoanStatus: This plot is very helpful, in the first plot I can see that most borrowers are in the 36-month term, and that a large number completed their loan.

  • IncomeVerifiable vs LoanStatus: In the second plot I see that the data is very imbalance, most of borrowers have a verified income

  • EmploymentStatus vs LoanStatus: In the third plot I can see that most borrowers are employed and there is a large number of completed loans on it
